article.description:
Brandon Heath scored six of his 22 points in the
final 1:08 of overtime to help San Diego State beat Wyoming 69-64
in the championship of the Mountain West Conference tournament
Saturday night.
article.headline: Heath's late heroics lift SDSU into NCAA Tournament
article.linkText: Heath's late heroics lift SDSU into NCAA Tournament
article.story: DENVER (AP) -- After his team shot 28 percent, San Diego State coach Steve Fisher opened his postgame news conference with a stunning announcement. "The thing that most impressed me was the way we shot the ball," he said. Then, like a comedy club master, the 60-year-old coach delivered his punch line: "In overtime." Brandon Heath scored eight of his 22 points in overtime, including six in the final 1:08, to help San Diego State beat Wyoming 69-64 in the championship of the Mountain West Conference tournament Saturday night. The Aztecs were 3-of-5 from the floor and 7-of-8 from the line in the extra period. Kyle Spain, who missed a shot underneath that could have won it in regulation, sank three of four free throws in the final 11 seconds to clinch the Aztecs' second NCAA Tournament berth in Fisher's seven seasons. The Cowboys (14-18) were close to heading to the postseason despite a losing record when they took a four-point lead with 2:18 left in overtime. But Heath, who missed 20 of 27 shots, suddenly found his touch. "My name was called. I just tried to answer," Heath said. Heath's running 6-footer tied it at 62 with just over a minute left and his jumper off a sweet spin move put the Aztecs ahead 64-63 with 35 seconds remaining. Then, he sank two free throws with 19 seconds left to make it 66-63. After Spain hit one of two free throws for a 67-64 lead, Wyoming's Steve Leven misfired on a 3-pointer with 3 seconds left and Spain got the ball, was fouled and made two more free throws with 1.8 seconds to play. Cowboys guard Brad Jones (15 points) sent the game into overtime at 56 when he sank two free throws with 7 seconds left in regulation after tournament MVP Marcus Slaughter fouled out. Slaughter finished with 16 points and 13 rebounds, and Spain had 11 points and 12 boards. For the tournament, Slaughter had 49 points and 46 rebounds, and he excitedly raced around the court with the net around his neck after Fisher tossed it to him from atop the ladder after snipping the final string. Freshman Brandon Ewing scored 22 points to lead seventh-seeded Wyoming, which upset Air Force and Utah this week amid speculation that coach Steve McClain would be fired after the season. "As competitors, we're definitely disappointed about the outcome but we're pleased with how we played," Wyoming's Justin Williams said. "We played hard to the finish, all 45 minutes. We played as hard as we ever played." The Cowboys used their superb inside game to hang with the heavily favored Aztecs, but San Diego State, the league's best rebounding team, got 18 second-chance points to Wyoming's nine. "We go to the glass and that is what we had to do," Fisher said. "We weren't shooting the ball well and had to find a way to get points. We got them off rebounds." Playing in their first conference championship game since 1988, the Cowboys were hoping to become the first sub-.500 team to win the MWC tournament and also the seventh school in the league's 7-year history to cut down the nets. Instead, the Aztecs became the first top seed to win the conference tournament since UNLV did it in 2000, and they avoided having to depend on an at-large bid to the NCAA Tournament. Even though the Aztecs set a school record for victories in the Division I era at San Diego State and won their first regular-season conference crown since 1978, their RPI rating was hovering in the 60s, putting them squarely on the bubble without a win Saturday night. McClain will soon meet with athletic director Gary Barta, who could cut him loose with a $535,000 buyout and four years left on his contract. He is 140-100 in eight seasons with the Cowboys. In his first five seasons, McClain guided the Cowboys to three NITs and to the second round of the NCAA tournament in 2002. But they've slipped in recent years, leading to calls for his ouster. The Cowboys nearly made it impossible for that to happen. After all, how could a coach get canned after leading his team to the NCAA Tournament? But they came up just short. "This wasn't about Steve McClain. This was about a group of kids that invested and I am proud of them," McClain said in a halting voice. "They never let it be a distraction."
